<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n58063b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n58" href="#n58063b">N58 (VI.B.30)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n58all.htm#n58063b"> 63(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> older the word / the richer</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In this Chinese shows its advantage. Its etymology is constantly visible. It retains the creative impulse and process, visible and at work. After thousands of years the lines of metaphoric advance are still shown, and in many cases actually retained in the meaning. Thus <mark>a word</mark>, instead of growing gradually poorer and poorer as with us, <mark>becomes richer and still more rich from age to age</mark>, almost consciously luminous. Its uses in national philosophy and history, in biography and in poetry, throw about it a nimbus of meanings. <small> Ernest Fenollosa, &ldquo;The Chinese Written Character as a Medium for Poetry&rdquo;, in <a name="EFCW" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EFCW"><cite title="source">Instigations of Ezra Pound</cite></a> (1920) 378f</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
